Stytch - <br>
<br>
Ebonics is the term given (by whom I do not know) to some flavor of American black slang.  Perhaps 7 or so years ago, the Oakland school district sought to teach it as a legitimate alternative to the formal rules of American English.  They immediately ran into criticism from almost all educators, of whatever ethnicity.  Many black leaders expressed sympathy for the motivations (give inner city youth some self esteem and validation), but condemned the proposal as dangerous (what better way to keep kids down that to teach them to speak in a manner which is gauranteed to dispose people badly towards them), poorly defined (who gets to say just what ebonics is, anyway?) and basically at odds with common sense.  Ebonics, to my recollection, was NEVER taught in any public school, and the proponents of it pretty quickly piped down.<br>
<br>
Lots of accents make one sound ignorant to my ears.  Inner city Boston is probably my favorite to pick on.  I have some cousins who grew up in Haverhill, MA.  Good lord, when they talk like that, they sound downright stupid!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
